308 // Generates a random number from [0, range), using a Linear
309 // Congruential Generator (LCG). Crashes if 'range' is 0 or greater
310 // than kMaxRange.
311 UInt32 Random::Generate(UInt32 range) {
312  // These constants are the same as are used in glibc's rand(3).
313  state_ = (1103515245U*state_ + 12345U) % kMaxRange;
314 
315  GTEST_CHECK_(range > 0)
316  << "Cannot generate a number in the range [0, 0).";
317  GTEST_CHECK_(range <= kMaxRange)
318  << "Generation of a number in [0, " << range << ") was requested, "
319  << "but this can only generate numbers in [0, " << kMaxRange << ").";
320 
321  // Converting via modulus introduces a bit of downward bias, but
322  // it's simple, and a linear congruential generator isn't too good
323  // to begin with.
324  return state_ % range;
325 }

332 // Iterates over a vector of TestCases, keeping a running sum of the
333 // results of calling a given int-returning method on each.
334 // Returns the sum.
335 static int SumOverTestCaseList(const std::vector<TestCase*>& case_list,
336  int (TestCase::*method)() const) {
337  int sum = 0;
338  for (size_t i = 0; i < case_list.size(); i++) {
339  sum += (case_list[i]->*method)();
340  }
341  return sum;
342 }

413 // Returns the output format, or "" for normal printed output.
414 std::string UnitTestOptions::GetOutputFormat() {
415  const char* const gtest_output_flag = GTEST_FLAG(output).c_str();
416  if (gtest_output_flag == NULL) return std::string("");
417 
418  const char* const colon = strchr(gtest_output_flag, ':');
419  return (colon == NULL) ?
420  std::string(gtest_output_flag) :
421  std::string(gtest_output_flag, colon - gtest_output_flag);
422 }

424 // Returns the name of the requested output file, or the default if none
425 // was explicitly specified.
426 std::string UnitTestOptions::GetAbsolutePathToOutputFile() {
427  const char* const gtest_output_flag = GTEST_FLAG(output).c_str();
428  if (gtest_output_flag == NULL)
429  return "";
430 
431  const char* const colon = strchr(gtest_output_flag, ':');
432  if (colon == NULL)
433  return internal::FilePath::ConcatPaths(
434  internal::FilePath(
435  UnitTest::GetInstance()->original_working_dir()),
436  internal::FilePath(kDefaultOutputFile)).string();
437 
438  internal::FilePath output_name(colon + 1);
439  if (!output_name.IsAbsolutePath())
440  // TODO(wan@google.com): on Windows \some\path is not an absolute
441  // path (as its meaning depends on the current drive), yet the
442  // following logic for turning it into an absolute path is wrong.
443  // Fix it.
444  output_name = internal::FilePath::ConcatPaths(
445  internal::FilePath(UnitTest::GetInstance()->original_working_dir()),
446  internal::FilePath(colon + 1));
447 
448  if (!output_name.IsDirectory())
449  return output_name.string();
450 
451  internal::FilePath result(internal::FilePath::GenerateUniqueFileName(
452  output_name, internal::GetCurrentExecutableName(),
453  GetOutputFormat().c_str()));
454  return result.string();
455 }

457 // Returns true iff the wildcard pattern matches the string. The
458 // first ':' or '\0' character in pattern marks the end of it.
459 //
460 // This recursive algorithm isn't very efficient, but is clear and
461 // works well enough for matching test names, which are short.
462 bool UnitTestOptions::PatternMatchesString(const char *pattern,
463  const char *str) {
464  switch (*pattern) {
465  case '\0':
466  case ':': // Either ':' or '\0' marks the end of the pattern.
467  return *str == '\0';
468  case '?': // Matches any single character.
469  return *str != '\0' && PatternMatchesString(pattern + 1, str + 1);
470  case '*': // Matches any string (possibly empty) of characters.
471  return (*str != '\0' && PatternMatchesString(pattern, str + 1)) ||
472  PatternMatchesString(pattern + 1, str);
473  default: // Non-special character. Matches itself.
474  return *pattern == *str &&
475  PatternMatchesString(pattern + 1, str + 1);
476  }
477 }
478 
479 bool UnitTestOptions::MatchesFilter(
480  const std::string& name, const char* filter) {
481  const char *cur_pattern = filter;
482  for (;;) {
483  if (PatternMatchesString(cur_pattern, name.c_str())) {
484  return true;
485  }
486 
487  // Finds the next pattern in the filter.
488  cur_pattern = strchr(cur_pattern, ':');
489 
490  // Returns if no more pattern can be found.
491  if (cur_pattern == NULL) {
492  return false;
493  }
494 
495  // Skips the pattern separater (the ':' character).
496  cur_pattern++;
497  }
498 }

500 // Returns true iff the user-specified filter matches the test case
501 // name and the test name.
502 bool UnitTestOptions::FilterMatchesTest(const std::string &test_case_name,
503  const std::string &test_name) {
504  const std::string& full_name = test_case_name + "." + test_name.c_str();
505 
506  // Split --gtest_filter at '-', if there is one, to separate into
507  // positive filter and negative filter portions
508  const char* const p = GTEST_FLAG(filter).c_str();
509  const char* const dash = strchr(p, '-');
510  std::string positive;
511  std::string negative;
512  if (dash == NULL) {
513  positive = GTEST_FLAG(filter).c_str(); // Whole string is a positive filter
514  negative = "";
515  } else {
516  positive = std::string(p, dash); // Everything up to the dash
517  negative = std::string(dash + 1); // Everything after the dash
518  if (positive.empty()) {
519  // Treat '-test1' as the same as '*-test1'
520  positive = kUniversalFilter;
521  }
522  }
523 
524  // A filter is a colon-separated list of patterns. It matches a
525  // test if any pattern in it matches the test.
526  return (MatchesFilter(full_name, positive.c_str()) &&
527  !MatchesFilter(full_name, negative.c_str()));
528 }

530 #if GTEST_HAS_SEH
531 // Returns EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER if Google Test should handle the
532 // given SEH exception, or EXCEPTION_CONTINUE_SEARCH otherwise.
533 // This function is useful as an __except condition.
534 int UnitTestOptions::GTestShouldProcessSEH(DWORD exception_code) {
535  // Google Test should handle a SEH exception if:
536  // 1. the user wants it to, AND
537  // 2. this is not a breakpoint exception, AND
538  // 3. this is not a C++ exception (VC++ implements them via SEH,
539  // apparently).
540  //
541  // SEH exception code for C++ exceptions.
542  // (see http://support.microsoft.com/kb/185294 for more information).
543  const DWORD kCxxExceptionCode = 0xe06d7363;
544 
545  bool should_handle = true;
546 
547  if (!GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions))
548  should_handle = false;
549  else if (exception_code == EXCEPTION_BREAKPOINT)
550  should_handle = false;
551  else if (exception_code == kCxxExceptionCode)
552  should_handle = false;
553 
554  return should_handle ? EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER : EXCEPTION_CONTINUE_SEARCH;
555 }
556 #endif // GTEST_HAS_SEH

580 void ScopedFakeTestPartResultReporter::Init() {
581  internal::UnitTestImpl* const impl = internal::GetUnitTestImpl();
582  if (intercept_mode_ == INTERCEPT_ALL_THREADS) {
583  old_reporter_ = impl->GetGlobalTestPartResultReporter();
584  impl->SetGlobalTestPartResultReporter(this);
585  } else {
586  old_reporter_ = impl->GetTestPartResultReporterForCurrentThread();
587  impl->SetTestPartResultReporterForCurrentThread(this);
588  }
589 }

597  } else {

599  }

611 // Returns the type ID of ::testing::Test. We should always call this
612 // instead of GetTypeId< ::testing::Test>() to get the type ID of
613 // testing::Test. This is to work around a suspected linker bug when
614 // using Google Test as a framework on Mac OS X. The bug causes
615 // GetTypeId< ::testing::Test>() to return different values depending
616 // on whether the call is from the Google Test framework itself or
617 // from user test code. GetTestTypeId() is guaranteed to always
618 // return the same value, as it always calls GetTypeId<>() from the
619 // gtest.cc, which is within the Google Test framework.
620 TypeId GetTestTypeId() {
621  return GetTypeId<Test>();
622 }

628 // This predicate-formatter checks that 'results' contains a test part
629 // failure of the given type and that the failure message contains the
630 // given substring.
631 AssertionResult HasOneFailure(const char* /* results_expr */,
632  const char* /* type_expr */,
633  const char* /* substr_expr */,
634  const TestPartResultArray& results,
635  TestPartResult::Type type,
636  const std::string& substr) {
637  const std::string expected(type == TestPartResult::kFatalFailure ?
638  "1 fatal failure" :
639  "1 non-fatal failure");
640  Message msg;
641  if (results.size() != 1) {
642  msg << "Expected: " << expected << "\n"
643  << " Actual: " << results.size() << " failures";
644  for (int i = 0; i < results.size(); i++) {
645  msg << "\n" << results.GetTestPartResult(i);
646  }
647  return AssertionFailure() << msg;
648  }
649 
650  const TestPartResult& r = results.GetTestPartResult(0);
651  if (r.type() != type) {
652  return AssertionFailure() << "Expected: " << expected << "\n"
653  << " Actual:\n"
654  << r;
655  }
656 
657  if (strstr(r.message(), substr.c_str()) == NULL) {
658  return AssertionFailure() << "Expected: " << expected << " containing \""
659  << substr << "\"\n"
660  << " Actual:\n"
661  << r;
662  }
663 
664  return AssertionSuccess();
665 }

802 // Returns the current time in milliseconds.
803 TimeInMillis GetTimeInMillis() {
804 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE || defined(__BORLANDC__)
805  // Difference between 1970-01-01 and 1601-01-01 in milliseconds.
806  // http://analogous.blogspot.com/2005/04/epoch.html
807  const TimeInMillis kJavaEpochToWinFileTimeDelta =
808  static_cast<TimeInMillis>(116444736UL) * 100000UL;
809  const DWORD kTenthMicrosInMilliSecond = 10000;
810 
811  SYSTEMTIME now_systime;
812  FILETIME now_filetime;
813  ULARGE_INTEGER now_int64;
814  // TODO(kenton@google.com): Shouldn't this just use
815  // GetSystemTimeAsFileTime()?
816  GetSystemTime(&now_systime);
817  if (SystemTimeToFileTime(&now_systime, &now_filetime)) {
818  now_int64.LowPart = now_filetime.dwLowDateTime;
819  now_int64.HighPart = now_filetime.dwHighDateTime;
820  now_int64.QuadPart = (now_int64.QuadPart / kTenthMicrosInMilliSecond) -
821  kJavaEpochToWinFileTimeDelta;
822  return now_int64.QuadPart;
823  }
824  return 0;
825 #elif GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_HAS_GETTIMEOFDAY_
826  __timeb64 now;
827 
828  // MSVC 8 deprecates _ftime64(), so we want to suppress warning 4996
829  // (deprecated function) there.
830  // TODO(kenton@google.com): Use GetTickCount()? Or use
831  // SystemTimeToFileTime()
832  GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_PUSH_(4996)
833  _ftime64(&now);
834  GTEST_DISABLE_MSC_WARNINGS_POP_()
835 
836  return static_cast<TimeInMillis>(now.time) * 1000 + now.millitm;
837 #elif GTEST_HAS_GETTIMEOFDAY_
838  struct timeval now;
839  gettimeofday(&now, NULL);
840  return static_cast<TimeInMillis>(now.tv_sec) * 1000 + now.tv_usec / 1000;
841 #else
842 # error "Don't know how to get the current time on your system."
843 #endif
844 }

851 // Creates a UTF-16 wide string from the given ANSI string, allocating
852 // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return
853 // value using delete[]. Returns the wide string, or NULL if the
854 // input is NULL.
855 LPCWSTR String::AnsiToUtf16(const char* ansi) {
856  if (!ansi) return NULL;
857  const int length = strlen(ansi);
858  const int unicode_length =
859  MultiByteToWideChar(CP_ACP, 0, ansi, length,
860  NULL, 0);
861  WCHAR* unicode = new WCHAR[unicode_length + 1];
862  MultiByteToWideChar(CP_ACP, 0, ansi, length,
863  unicode, unicode_length);
864  unicode[unicode_length] = 0;
865  return unicode;
866 }

869 // memory using new. The caller is responsible for deleting the return

886 // Compares two C strings. Returns true iff they have the same content.
887 //
888 // Unlike strcmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s). A NULL
889 // C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
890 // including the empty string.
891 bool String::CStringEquals(const char * lhs, const char * rhs) {
892  if ( lhs == NULL ) return rhs == NULL;
893 
894  if ( rhs == NULL ) return false;
895 
896  return strcmp(lhs, rhs) == 0;

901 // Converts an array of wide chars to a narrow string using the UTF-8
902 // encoding, and streams the result to the given Message object.
903 static void StreamWideCharsToMessage(const wchar_t* wstr, size_t length,
904  Message* msg) {
905  for (size_t i = 0; i != length; ) { // NOLINT
906  if (wstr[i] != L'\0') {
907  *msg << WideStringToUtf8(wstr + i, static_cast<int>(length - i));
908  while (i != length && wstr[i] != L'\0')
909  i++;
910  } else {
911  *msg << '\0';
912  i++;
913  }
914  }
915 }

917 #endif // GTEST_HAS_STD_WSTRING || GTEST_HAS_GLOBAL_WSTRING
918 
919 void SplitString(const ::std::string& str, char delimiter,
920  ::std::vector< ::std::string>* dest) {
921  ::std::vector< ::std::string> parsed;
922  ::std::string::size_type pos = 0;
923  while (::testing::internal::AlwaysTrue()) {
924  const ::std::string::size_type colon = str.find(delimiter, pos);
925  if (colon == ::std::string::npos) {
926  parsed.push_back(str.substr(pos));
927  break;
928  } else {
929  parsed.push_back(str.substr(pos, colon - pos));
930  pos = colon + 1;
931  }
932  }
933  dest->swap(parsed);
934 }

1024 namespace edit_distance {
1025 std::vector<EditType> CalculateOptimalEdits(const std::vector<size_t>& left,
1026  const std::vector<size_t>& right) {
1027  std::vector<std::vector<double> > costs(
1028  left.size() + 1, std::vector<double>(right.size() + 1));
1029  std::vector<std::vector<EditType> > best_move(
1030  left.size() + 1, std::vector<EditType>(right.size() + 1));
1031 
1032  // Populate for empty right.
1033  for (size_t l_i = 0; l_i < costs.size(); ++l_i) {
1034  costs[l_i][0] = static_cast<double>(l_i);
1035  best_move[l_i][0] = kRemove;
1036  }
1037  // Populate for empty left.
1038  for (size_t r_i = 1; r_i < costs[0].size(); ++r_i) {
1039  costs[0][r_i] = static_cast<double>(r_i);
1040  best_move[0][r_i] = kAdd;
1041  }
1042 
1043  for (size_t l_i = 0; l_i < left.size(); ++l_i) {
1044  for (size_t r_i = 0; r_i < right.size(); ++r_i) {
1045  if (left[l_i] == right[r_i]) {
1046  // Found a match. Consume it.
1047  costs[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = costs[l_i][r_i];
1048  best_move[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = kMatch;
1049  continue;
1050  }
1051 
1052  const double add = costs[l_i + 1][r_i];
1053  const double remove = costs[l_i][r_i + 1];
1054  const double replace = costs[l_i][r_i];
1055  if (add < remove && add < replace) {
1056  costs[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = add + 1;
1057  best_move[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = kAdd;
1058  } else if (remove < add && remove < replace) {
1059  costs[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = remove + 1;
1060  best_move[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = kRemove;
1061  } else {
1062  // We make replace a little more expensive than add/remove to lower
1063  // their priority.
1064  costs[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = replace + 1.00001;
1065  best_move[l_i + 1][r_i + 1] = kReplace;
1066  }
1067  }
1068  }
1069 
1070  // Reconstruct the best path. We do it in reverse order.
1071  std::vector<EditType> best_path;
1072  for (size_t l_i = left.size(), r_i = right.size(); l_i > 0 || r_i > 0;) {
1073  EditType move = best_move[l_i][r_i];
1074  best_path.push_back(move);
1075  l_i -= move != kAdd;
1076  r_i -= move != kRemove;
1077  }
1078  std::reverse(best_path.begin(), best_path.end());
1079  return best_path;
1080 }

1101 std::vector<EditType> CalculateOptimalEdits(
1102  const std::vector<std::string>& left,
1103  const std::vector<std::string>& right) {

1119 // Helper class that holds the state for one hunk and prints it out to the
1120 // stream.
1121 // It reorders adds/removes when possible to group all removes before all
1122 // adds. It also adds the hunk header before printint into the stream.
1123 class Hunk {
1124  public:
1125  Hunk(size_t left_start, size_t right_start)
1126  : left_start_(left_start),
1127  right_start_(right_start),
1128  adds_(),
1129  removes_(),
1130  common_() {}
1131 
1132  void PushLine(char edit, const char* line) {
1133  switch (edit) {
1134  case ' ':
1135  ++common_;
1136  FlushEdits();
1137  hunk_.push_back(std::make_pair(' ', line));
1138  break;
1139  case '-':
1140  ++removes_;
1141  hunk_removes_.push_back(std::make_pair('-', line));
1142  break;
1143  case '+':
1144  ++adds_;
1145  hunk_adds_.push_back(std::make_pair('+', line));
1146  break;
1147  }
1148  }
1149 
1150  void PrintTo(std::ostream* os) {
1151  PrintHeader(os);
1152  FlushEdits();
1153  for (std::list<std::pair<char, const char*> >::const_iterator it =
1154  hunk_.begin();
1155  it != hunk_.end(); ++it) {
1156  *os << it->first << it->second << "\n";
1157  }
1158  }
1159 
1160  bool has_edits() const { return adds_ || removes_; }
1161 
1162  private:
1163  void FlushEdits() {
1164  hunk_.splice(hunk_.end(), hunk_removes_);
1165  hunk_.splice(hunk_.end(), hunk_adds_);
1166  }
1167 
1168  // Print a unified diff header for one hunk.
1169  // The format is
1170  // "@@ -<left_start>,<left_length> +<right_start>,<right_length> @@"
1171  // where the left/right parts are ommitted if unnecessary.
1172  void PrintHeader(std::ostream* ss) const {
1173  *ss << "@@ ";
1174  if (removes_) {
1175  *ss << "-" << left_start_ << "," << (removes_ + common_);
1176  }
1177  if (removes_ && adds_) {
1178  *ss << " ";
1179  }
1180  if (adds_) {
1181  *ss << "+" << right_start_ << "," << (adds_ + common_);
1182  }
1183  *ss << " @@\n";
1184  }
1185 
1186  size_t left_start_, right_start_;
1187  size_t adds_, removes_, common_;
1188  std::list<std::pair<char, const char*> > hunk_, hunk_adds_, hunk_removes_;
1189 };
1190 
1191 } // namespace
1192 
1193 // Create a list of diff hunks in Unified diff format.
1194 // Each hunk has a header generated by PrintHeader above plus a body with
1195 // lines prefixed with ' ' for no change, '-' for deletion and '+' for
1196 // addition.
1197 // 'context' represents the desired unchanged prefix/suffix around the diff.
1198 // If two hunks are close enough that their contexts overlap, then they are
1199 // joined into one hunk.
1200 std::string CreateUnifiedDiff(const std::vector<std::string>& left,
1201  const std::vector<std::string>& right,
1202  size_t context) {
1203  const std::vector<EditType> edits = CalculateOptimalEdits(left, right);
1204 
1205  size_t l_i = 0, r_i = 0, edit_i = 0;
1206  std::stringstream ss;
1207  while (edit_i < edits.size()) {
1208  // Find first edit.
1209  while (edit_i < edits.size() && edits[edit_i] == kMatch) {
1210  ++l_i;
1211  ++r_i;
1212  ++edit_i;
1213  }
1214 
1215  // Find the first line to include in the hunk.
1216  const size_t prefix_context = std::min(l_i, context);
1217  Hunk hunk(l_i - prefix_context + 1, r_i - prefix_context + 1);
1218  for (size_t i = prefix_context; i > 0; --i) {
1219  hunk.PushLine(' ', left[l_i - i].c_str());
1220  }
1221 
1222  // Iterate the edits until we found enough suffix for the hunk or the input
1223  // is over.
1224  size_t n_suffix = 0;
1225  for (; edit_i < edits.size(); ++edit_i) {
1226  if (n_suffix >= context) {
1227  // Continue only if the next hunk is very close.
1228  std::vector<EditType>::const_iterator it = edits.begin() + edit_i;
1229  while (it != edits.end() && *it == kMatch) ++it;
1230  if (it == edits.end() || (it - edits.begin()) - edit_i >= context) {
1231  // There is no next edit or it is too far away.
1232  break;
1233  }
1234  }
1235 
1236  EditType edit = edits[edit_i];
1237  // Reset count when a non match is found.
1238  n_suffix = edit == kMatch ? n_suffix + 1 : 0;
1239 
1240  if (edit == kMatch || edit == kRemove || edit == kReplace) {
1241  hunk.PushLine(edit == kMatch ? ' ' : '-', left[l_i].c_str());
1242  }
1243  if (edit == kAdd || edit == kReplace) {
1244  hunk.PushLine('+', right[r_i].c_str());
1245  }
1246 
1247  // Advance indices, depending on edit type.
1248  l_i += edit != kAdd;
1249  r_i += edit != kRemove;
1250  }
1251 
1252  if (!hunk.has_edits()) {
1253  // We are done. We don't want this hunk.
1254  break;
1255  }
1256 
1257  hunk.PrintTo(&ss);
1258  }
1259  return ss.str();
1260 }
1261 
1262 } // namespace edit_distance

1266 // The string representation of the values received in EqFailure() are already
1267 // escaped. Split them on escaped '\n' boundaries. Leave all other escaped
1268 // characters the same.
1269 std::vector<std::string> SplitEscapedString(const std::string& str) {
1270  std::vector<std::string> lines;
1271  size_t start = 0, end = str.size();
1272  if (end > 2 && str[0] == '"' && str[end - 1] == '"') {
1273  ++start;
1274  --end;
1275  }
1276  bool escaped = false;
1277  for (size_t i = start; i + 1 < end; ++i) {
1278  if (escaped) {
1279  escaped = false;
1280  if (str[i] == 'n') {
1281  lines.push_back(str.substr(start, i - start - 1));
1282  start = i + 1;
1283  }
1284  } else {
1285  escaped = str[i] == '\\';
1286  }
1287  }
1288  lines.push_back(str.substr(start, end - start));
1289  return lines;
1290 }

1294 // Constructs and returns the message for an equality assertion
1295 // (e.g. ASSERT_EQ, EXPECT_STREQ, etc) failure.
1296 //
1297 // The first four parameters are the expressions used in the assertion
1298 // and their values, as strings. For example, for ASSERT_EQ(foo, bar)
1299 // where foo is 5 and bar is 6, we have:
1300 //
1301 // lhs_expression: "foo"
1302 // rhs_expression: "bar"
1303 // lhs_value: "5"
1304 // rhs_value: "6"
1305 //
1306 // The ignoring_case parameter is true iff the assertion is a
1307 // *_STRCASEEQ*. When it's true, the string "Ignoring case" will
1308 // be inserted into the message.
1309 AssertionResult EqFailure(const char* lhs_expression,
1310  const char* rhs_expression,
1311  const std::string& lhs_value,
1312  const std::string& rhs_value,
1313  bool ignoring_case) {
1314  Message msg;
1315  msg << " Expected: " << lhs_expression;
1316  if (lhs_value != lhs_expression) {
1317  msg << "\n Which is: " << lhs_value;
1318  }
1319  msg << "\nTo be equal to: " << rhs_expression;
1320  if (rhs_value != rhs_expression) {
1321  msg << "\n Which is: " << rhs_value;
1322  }
1323 
1324  if (ignoring_case) {
1325  msg << "\nIgnoring case";
1326  }
1327 
1328  if (!lhs_value.empty() && !rhs_value.empty()) {
1329  const std::vector<std::string> lhs_lines =
1330  SplitEscapedString(lhs_value);
1331  const std::vector<std::string> rhs_lines =
1332  SplitEscapedString(rhs_value);
1333  if (lhs_lines.size() > 1 || rhs_lines.size() > 1) {
1334  msg << "\nWith diff:\n"
1335  << edit_distance::CreateUnifiedDiff(lhs_lines, rhs_lines);
1336  }
1337  }
1338 
1339  return AssertionFailure() << msg;
1340 }
1341 
1342 // Constructs a failure message for Boolean assertions such as EXPECT_TRUE.
1343 std::string GetBoolAssertionFailureMessage(
1344  const AssertionResult& assertion_result,
1345  const char* expression_text,
1346  const char* actual_predicate_value,
1347  const char* expected_predicate_value) {
1348  const char* actual_message = assertion_result.message();
1349  Message msg;
1350  msg << "Value of: " << expression_text
1351  << "\n Actual: " << actual_predicate_value;
1352  if (actual_message[0] != '\0')
1353  msg << " (" << actual_message << ")";
1354  msg << "\nExpected: " << expected_predicate_value;
1355  return msg.GetString();
1356 }

1379 // Helper template for implementing FloatLE() and DoubleLE().
1380 template <typename RawType>
1381 AssertionResult FloatingPointLE(const char* expr1,
1382  const char* expr2,
1383  RawType val1,
1384  RawType val2) {
1385  // Returns success if val1 is less than val2,
1386  if (val1 < val2) {
1387  return AssertionSuccess();
1388  }
1389 
1390  // or if val1 is almost equal to val2.
1391  const FloatingPoint<RawType> lhs(val1), rhs(val2);
1392  if (lhs.AlmostEquals(rhs)) {
1393  return AssertionSuccess();
1394  }
1395 
1396  // Note that the above two checks will both fail if either val1 or
1397  // val2 is NaN, as the IEEE floating-point standard requires that
1398  // any predicate involving a NaN must return false.
1399 
1400  ::std::stringstream val1_ss;
1401  val1_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
1402  << val1;
1403 
1404  ::std::stringstream val2_ss;
1405  val2_ss << std::setprecision(std::numeric_limits<RawType>::digits10 + 2)
1406  << val2;
1407 
1408  return AssertionFailure()
1409  << "Expected: (" << expr1 << ") <= (" << expr2 << ")\n"
1410  << " Actual: " << StringStreamToString(&val1_ss) << " vs "
1411  << StringStreamToString(&val2_ss);
1412 }

1548 // Helper functions for implementing IsSubString() and IsNotSubstring().

1550 // This group of overloaded functions return true iff needle is a
1551 // substring of haystack. NULL is considered a substring of itself
1552 // only.
1553 
1554 bool IsSubstringPred(const char* needle, const char* haystack) {
1555  if (needle == NULL || haystack == NULL)
1556  return needle == haystack;
1557 
1558  return strstr(haystack, needle) != NULL;
1559 }
1560 
1561 bool IsSubstringPred(const wchar_t* needle, const wchar_t* haystack) {
1562  if (needle == NULL || haystack == NULL)
1563  return needle == haystack;
1564 
1565  return wcsstr(haystack, needle) != NULL;
1566 }

1568 // StringType here can be either ::std::string or ::std::wstring.
1569 template <typename StringType>
1570 bool IsSubstringPred(const StringType& needle,
1571  const StringType& haystack) {
1572  return haystack.find(needle) != StringType::npos;
1573 }
1574 
1575 // This function implements either IsSubstring() or IsNotSubstring(),
1576 // depending on the value of the expected_to_be_substring parameter.
1577 // StringType here can be const char*, const wchar_t*, ::std::string,
1578 // or ::std::wstring.
1579 template <typename StringType>
1580 AssertionResult IsSubstringImpl(
1581  bool expected_to_be_substring,
1582  const char* needle_expr, const char* haystack_expr,
1583  const StringType& needle, const StringType& haystack) {
1584  if (IsSubstringPred(needle, haystack) == expected_to_be_substring)

1587  const bool is_wide_string = sizeof(needle[0]) > 1;
1588  const char* const begin_string_quote = is_wide_string ? "L\"" : "\"";
1589  return AssertionFailure()
1590  << "Value of: " << needle_expr << "\n"
1591  << " Actual: " << begin_string_quote << needle << "\"\n"
1592  << "Expected: " << (expected_to_be_substring ? "" : "not ")
1593  << "a substring of " << haystack_expr << "\n"
1594  << "Which is: " << begin_string_quote << haystack << "\"";
1595 }

1659 // Helper function for IsHRESULT{SuccessFailure} predicates
1660 AssertionResult HRESULTFailureHelper(const char* expr,
1661  const char* expected,
1662  long hr) { // NOLINT
1663 # if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
1664 
1665  // Windows CE doesn't support FormatMessage.
1666  const char error_text[] = "";
1667 
1668 # else
1669 
1670  // Looks up the human-readable system message for the HRESULT code
1671  // and since we're not passing any params to FormatMessage, we don't
1672  // want inserts expanded.
1673  const DWORD kFlags = FORMAT_MESSAGE_FROM_SYSTEM |
1674  FORMAT_MESSAGE_IGNORE_INSERTS;
1675  const DWORD kBufSize = 4096;
1676  // Gets the system's human readable message string for this HRESULT.
1677  char error_text[kBufSize] = { '\0' };
1678  DWORD message_length = ::FormatMessageA(kFlags,
1679  0, // no source, we're asking system
1680  hr, // the error
1681  0, // no line width restrictions
1682  error_text, // output buffer
1683  kBufSize, // buf size
1684  NULL); // no arguments for inserts
1685  // Trims tailing white space (FormatMessage leaves a trailing CR-LF)
1686  for (; message_length && IsSpace(error_text[message_length - 1]);
1687  --message_length) {
1688  error_text[message_length - 1] = '\0';
1689  }
1690 
1691 # endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
1692 
1693  const std::string error_hex("0x" + String::FormatHexInt(hr));
1694  return ::testing::AssertionFailure()
1695  << "Expected: " << expr << " " << expected << ".\n"
1696  << " Actual: " << error_hex << " " << error_text << "\n";
1697 }

1717 // Utility functions for encoding Unicode text (wide strings) in
1718 // UTF-8.
1719 
1720 // A Unicode code-point can have upto 21 bits, and is encoded in UTF-8
1721 // like this:
1722 //
1723 // Code-point length Encoding
1724 // 0 - 7 bits 0xxxxxxx
1725 // 8 - 11 bits 110xxxxx 10xxxxxx
1726 // 12 - 16 bits 1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
1727 // 17 - 21 bits 11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
1728 
1729 // The maximum code-point a one-byte UTF-8 sequence can represent.
1730 const UInt32 kMaxCodePoint1 = (static_cast<UInt32>(1) << 7) - 1;
1731 
1732 // The maximum code-point a two-byte UTF-8 sequence can represent.
1733 const UInt32 kMaxCodePoint2 = (static_cast<UInt32>(1) << (5 + 6)) - 1;
1734 
1735 // The maximum code-point a three-byte UTF-8 sequence can represent.
1736 const UInt32 kMaxCodePoint3 = (static_cast<UInt32>(1) << (4 + 2*6)) - 1;
1737 
1738 // The maximum code-point a four-byte UTF-8 sequence can represent.
1739 const UInt32 kMaxCodePoint4 = (static_cast<UInt32>(1) << (3 + 3*6)) - 1;
1740 
1741 // Chops off the n lowest bits from a bit pattern. Returns the n
1742 // lowest bits. As a side effect, the original bit pattern will be
1743 // shifted to the right by n bits.
1744 inline UInt32 ChopLowBits(UInt32* bits, int n) {
1745  const UInt32 low_bits = *bits & ((static_cast<UInt32>(1) << n) - 1);
1746  *bits >>= n;
1747  return low_bits;
1748 }
1749 
1750 // Converts a Unicode code point to a narrow string in UTF-8 encoding.
1751 // code_point parameter is of type UInt32 because wchar_t may not be
1752 // wide enough to contain a code point.
1753 // If the code_point is not a valid Unicode code point
1754 // (i.e. outside of Unicode range U+0 to U+10FFFF) it will be converted
1755 // to "(Invalid Unicode 0xXXXXXXXX)".
1756 std::string CodePointToUtf8(UInt32 code_point) {
1757  if (code_point > kMaxCodePoint4) {
1758  return "(Invalid Unicode 0x" + String::FormatHexInt(code_point) + ")";
1759  }
1760 
1761  char str[5]; // Big enough for the largest valid code point.
1762  if (code_point <= kMaxCodePoint1) {
1763  str[1] = '\0';
1764  str[0] = static_cast<char>(code_point); // 0xxxxxxx
1765  } else if (code_point <= kMaxCodePoint2) {
1766  str[2] = '\0';
1767  str[1] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1768  str[0] = static_cast<char>(0xC0 | code_point); // 110xxxxx
1769  } else if (code_point <= kMaxCodePoint3) {
1770  str[3] = '\0';
1771  str[2] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1772  str[1] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1773  str[0] = static_cast<char>(0xE0 | code_point); // 1110xxxx
1774  } else { // code_point <= kMaxCodePoint4
1775  str[4] = '\0';
1776  str[3] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1777  str[2] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1778  str[1] = static_cast<char>(0x80 | ChopLowBits(&code_point, 6)); // 10xxxxxx
1779  str[0] = static_cast<char>(0xF0 | code_point); // 11110xxx
1780  }
1781  return str;
1782 }
1783 
1784 // The following two functions only make sense if the the system
1785 // uses UTF-16 for wide string encoding. All supported systems
1786 // with 16 bit wchar_t (Windows, Cygwin, Symbian OS) do use UTF-16.
1787 
1788 // Determines if the arguments constitute UTF-16 surrogate pair
1789 // and thus should be combined into a single Unicode code point
1790 // using CreateCodePointFromUtf16SurrogatePair.
1791 inline bool IsUtf16SurrogatePair(wchar_t first, wchar_t second) {
1792  return sizeof(wchar_t) == 2 &&
1793  (first & 0xFC00) == 0xD800 && (second & 0xFC00) == 0xDC00;
1794 }
1795 
1796 // Creates a Unicode code point from UTF16 surrogate pair.
1797 inline UInt32 CreateCodePointFromUtf16SurrogatePair(wchar_t first,
1798  wchar_t second) {
1799  const UInt32 mask = (1 << 10) - 1;
1800  return (sizeof(wchar_t) == 2) ?
1801  (((first & mask) << 10) | (second & mask)) + 0x10000 :
1802  // This function should not be called when the condition is
1803  // false, but we provide a sensible default in case it is.
1804  static_cast<UInt32>(first);
1805 }
1806 
1807 // Converts a wide string to a narrow string in UTF-8 encoding.
1808 // The wide string is assumed to have the following encoding:
1809 // UTF-16 if sizeof(wchar_t) == 2 (on Windows, Cygwin, Symbian OS)
1810 // UTF-32 if sizeof(wchar_t) == 4 (on Linux)
1811 // Parameter str points to a null-terminated wide string.
1812 // Parameter num_chars may additionally limit the number
1813 // of wchar_t characters processed. -1 is used when the entire string
1814 // should be processed.
1815 // If the string contains code points that are not valid Unicode code points
1816 // (i.e. outside of Unicode range U+0 to U+10FFFF) they will be output
1817 // as '(Invalid Unicode 0xXXXXXXXX)'. If the string is in UTF16 encoding
1818 // and contains invalid UTF-16 surrogate pairs, values in those pairs
1819 // will be encoded as individual Unicode characters from Basic Normal Plane.
1820 std::string WideStringToUtf8(const wchar_t* str, int num_chars) {
1821  if (num_chars == -1)
1822  num_chars = static_cast<int>(wcslen(str));
1823 
1824  ::std::stringstream stream;
1825  for (int i = 0; i < num_chars; ++i) {
1826  UInt32 unicode_code_point;
1827 
1828  if (str[i] == L'\0') {
1829  break;
1830  } else if (i + 1 < num_chars && IsUtf16SurrogatePair(str[i], str[i + 1])) {
1831  unicode_code_point = CreateCodePointFromUtf16SurrogatePair(str[i],
1832  str[i + 1]);
1833  i++;
1834  } else {
1835  unicode_code_point = static_cast<UInt32>(str[i]);
1836  }
1837 
1838  stream << CodePointToUtf8(unicode_code_point);
1839  }
1840  return StringStreamToString(&stream);
1841 }

1845 std::string String::ShowWideCString(const wchar_t * wide_c_str) {
1846  if (wide_c_str == NULL) return "(null)";

1848  return internal::WideStringToUtf8(wide_c_str, -1);

1896 // Compares two C strings, ignoring case. Returns true iff they have
1897 // the same content.
1898 //
1899 // Unlike strcasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s). A
1900 // NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL C string,
1901 // including the empty string.
1902 bool String::CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(const char * lhs, const char * rhs) {
1903  if (lhs == NULL)
1904  return rhs == NULL;
1905  if (rhs == NULL)
1906  return false;
1907  return posix::StrCaseCmp(lhs, rhs) == 0;
1908 }
1909 
1910  // Compares two wide C strings, ignoring case. Returns true iff they
1911  // have the same content.
1912  //
1913  // Unlike wcscasecmp(), this function can handle NULL argument(s).
1914  // A NULL C string is considered different to any non-NULL wide C string,
1915  // including the empty string.
1916  // NB: The implementations on different platforms slightly differ.
1917  // On windows, this method uses _wcsicmp which compares according to LC_CTYPE
1918  // environment variable. On GNU platform this method uses wcscasecmp
1919  // which compares according to LC_CTYPE category of the current locale.
1920  // On MacOS X, it uses towlower, which also uses LC_CTYPE category of the
1921  // current locale.
1922 bool String::CaseInsensitiveWideCStringEquals(const wchar_t* lhs,
1923  const wchar_t* rhs) {
1924  if (lhs == NULL) return rhs == NULL;
1925 
1926  if (rhs == NULL) return false;
1927 
1928 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
1929  return _wcsicmp(lhs, rhs) == 0;
1930 #elif GTEST_OS_LINUX && !GTEST_OS_LINUX_ANDROID
1931  return wcscasecmp(lhs, rhs) == 0;
1932 #else
1933  // Android, Mac OS X and Cygwin don't define wcscasecmp.
1934  // Other unknown OSes may not define it either.
1935  wint_t left, right;
1936  do {
1937  left = towlower(*lhs++);
1938  right = towlower(*rhs++);
1939  } while (left && left == right);
1940  return left == right;
1941 #endif // OS selector
1942 }

1944 // Returns true iff str ends with the given suffix, ignoring case.

1946 bool String::EndsWithCaseInsensitive(

1948  const size_t str_len = str.length();

1951  CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(str.c_str() + str_len - suffix_len,
1952  suffix.c_str());

1977 // Converts the buffer in a stringstream to an std::string, converting NUL
1978 // bytes to "\\0" along the way.
1979 std::string StringStreamToString(::std::stringstream* ss) {
1980  const ::std::string& str = ss->str();
1981  const char* const start = str.c_str();
1982  const char* const end = start + str.length();
1983 
1984  std::string result;
1985  result.reserve(2 * (end - start));
1986  for (const char* ch = start; ch != end; ++ch) {
1987  if (*ch == '\0') {
1988  result += "\\0"; // Replaces NUL with "\\0";
1989  } else {
1990  result += *ch;
1991  }
1992  }
1993 
1994  return result;
1995 }

2261 // Google Test requires all tests in the same test case to use the same test
2262 // fixture class. This function checks if the current test has the
2263 // same fixture class as the first test in the current test case. If
2264 // yes, it returns true; otherwise it generates a Google Test failure and
2265 // returns false.
2266 bool Test::HasSameFixtureClass() {
2267  internal::UnitTestImpl* const impl = internal::GetUnitTestImpl();
2268  const TestCase* const test_case = impl->current_test_case();
2269 
2270  // Info about the first test in the current test case.
2271  const TestInfo* const first_test_info = test_case->test_info_list()[0];
2272  const internal::TypeId first_fixture_id = first_test_info->fixture_class_id_;
2273  const char* const first_test_name = first_test_info->name();
2274 
2275  // Info about the current test.
2276  const TestInfo* const this_test_info = impl->current_test_info();
2277  const internal::TypeId this_fixture_id = this_test_info->fixture_class_id_;
2278  const char* const this_test_name = this_test_info->name();
2279 
2280  if (this_fixture_id != first_fixture_id) {
2281  // Is the first test defined using TEST?
2282  const bool first_is_TEST = first_fixture_id == internal::GetTestTypeId();
2283  // Is this test defined using TEST?
2284  const bool this_is_TEST = this_fixture_id == internal::GetTestTypeId();
2285 
2286  if (first_is_TEST || this_is_TEST) {
2287  // Both TEST and TEST_F appear in same test case, which is incorrect.
2288  // Tell the user how to fix this.
2289 
2290  // Gets the name of the TEST and the name of the TEST_F. Note
2291  // that first_is_TEST and this_is_TEST cannot both be true, as
2292  // the fixture IDs are different for the two tests.
2293  const char* const TEST_name =
2294  first_is_TEST ? first_test_name : this_test_name;
2295  const char* const TEST_F_name =
2296  first_is_TEST ? this_test_name : first_test_name;
2297 
2298  ADD_FAILURE()
2299  << "All tests in the same test case must use the same test fixture\n"
2300  << "class, so mixing TEST_F and TEST in the same test case is\n"
2301  << "illegal. In test case " << this_test_info->test_case_name()
2302  << ",\n"
2303  << "test " << TEST_F_name << " is defined using TEST_F but\n"
2304  << "test " << TEST_name << " is defined using TEST. You probably\n"
2305  << "want to change the TEST to TEST_F or move it to another test\n"
2306  << "case.";
2307  } else {
2308  // Two fixture classes with the same name appear in two different
2309  // namespaces, which is not allowed. Tell the user how to fix this.
2310  ADD_FAILURE()
2311  << "All tests in the same test case must use the same test fixture\n"
2312  << "class. However, in test case "
2313  << this_test_info->test_case_name() << ",\n"
2314  << "you defined test " << first_test_name
2315  << " and test " << this_test_name << "\n"
2316  << "using two different test fixture classes. This can happen if\n"
2317  << "the two classes are from different namespaces or translation\n"
2318  << "units and have the same name. You should probably rename one\n"
2319  << "of the classes to put the tests into different test cases.";
2320  }
2321  return false;
2322  }
2323 
2324  return true;
2325 }

2374 // Runs the given method and handles SEH exceptions it throws, when
2375 // SEH is supported; returns the 0-value for type Result in case of an
2376 // SEH exception. (Microsoft compilers cannot handle SEH and C++
2377 // exceptions in the same function. Therefore, we provide a separate
2378 // wrapper function for handling SEH exceptions.)
2379 template <class T, typename Result>
2380 Result HandleSehExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2381  T* object, Result (T::*method)(), const char* location) {
2382 #if GTEST_HAS_SEH
2383  __try {
2384  return (object->*method)();
2385  } __except (internal::UnitTestOptions::GTestShouldProcessSEH( // NOLINT
2386  GetExceptionCode())) {
2387  // We create the exception message on the heap because VC++ prohibits
2388  // creation of objects with destructors on stack in functions using __try
2389  // (see error C2712).
2390  std::string* exception_message = FormatSehExceptionMessage(
2391  GetExceptionCode(), location);
2392  internal::ReportFailureInUnknownLocation(TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
2393  *exception_message);
2394  delete exception_message;
2395  return static_cast<Result>(0);
2396  }
2397 #else
2398  (void)location;
2399  return (object->*method)();
2400 #endif // GTEST_HAS_SEH
2401 }

2403 // Runs the given method and catches and reports C++ and/or SEH-style
2404 // exceptions, if they are supported; returns the 0-value for type
2405 // Result in case of an SEH exception.
2406 template <class T, typename Result>
2407 Result HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2408  T* object, Result (T::*method)(), const char* location) {
2409  // NOTE: The user code can affect the way in which Google Test handles
2410  // exceptions by setting GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions), but only before
2411  // RUN_ALL_TESTS() starts. It is technically possible to check the flag
2412  // after the exception is caught and either report or re-throw the
2413  // exception based on the flag's value:
2414  //
2415  // try {
2416  // // Perform the test method.
2417  // } catch (...) {
2418  // if (GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions))
2419  // // Report the exception as failure.
2420  // else
2421  // throw; // Re-throws the original exception.
2422  // }
2423  //
2424  // However, the purpose of this flag is to allow the program to drop into
2425  // the debugger when the exception is thrown. On most platforms, once the
2426  // control enters the catch block, the exception origin information is
2427  // lost and the debugger will stop the program at the point of the
2428  // re-throw in this function -- instead of at the point of the original
2429  // throw statement in the code under test. For this reason, we perform
2430  // the check early, sacrificing the ability to affect Google Test's
2431  // exception handling in the method where the exception is thrown.
2432  if (internal::GetUnitTestImpl()->catch_exceptions()) {
2433 #if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
2434  try {
2435  return HandleSehExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(object, method, location);
2436  } catch (const internal::GoogleTestFailureException&) { // NOLINT
2437  // This exception type can only be thrown by a failed Google
2438  // Test assertion with the intention of letting another testing
2439  // framework catch it. Therefore we just re-throw it.
2440  throw;
2441  } catch (const std::exception& e) { // NOLINT
2442  internal::ReportFailureInUnknownLocation(
2443  TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
2444  FormatCxxExceptionMessage(e.what(), location));
2445  } catch (...) { // NOLINT
2446  internal::ReportFailureInUnknownLocation(
2447  TestPartResult::kFatalFailure,
2448  FormatCxxExceptionMessage(NULL, location));
2449  }
2450  return static_cast<Result>(0);
2451 #else
2452  return HandleSehExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(object, method, location);
2453 #endif // GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
2454  } else {
2455  return (object->*method)();
2456  }
2457 }
2458 
2459 } // namespace internal
2460 
2461 // Runs the test and updates the test result.
2462 void Test::Run() {
2463  if (!HasSameFixtureClass()) return;
2464 
2465  internal::UnitTestImpl* const impl = internal::GetUnitTestImpl();
2466  impl->os_stack_trace_getter()->UponLeavingGTest();
2467  internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(this, &Test::SetUp, "SetUp()");
2468  // We will run the test only if SetUp() was successful.
2469  if (!HasFatalFailure()) {
2470  impl->os_stack_trace_getter()->UponLeavingGTest();
2471  internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2472  this, &Test::TestBody, "the test body");
2473  }
2474 
2475  // However, we want to clean up as much as possible. Hence we will
2476  // always call TearDown(), even if SetUp() or the test body has
2477  // failed.
2478  impl->os_stack_trace_getter()->UponLeavingGTest();
2479  internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2480  this, &Test::TearDown, "TearDown()");
2481 }

2625 // Creates the test object, runs it, records its result, and then
2626 // deletes it.
2627 void TestInfo::Run() {
2628  if (!should_run_) return;
2629 
2630  // Tells UnitTest where to store test result.
2631  internal::UnitTestImpl* const impl = internal::GetUnitTestImpl();
2632  impl->set_current_test_info(this);
2633 
2634  TestEventListener* repeater = UnitTest::GetInstance()->listeners().repeater();
2635 
2636  // Notifies the unit test event listeners that a test is about to start.
2637  repeater->OnTestStart(*this);
2638 
2639  const TimeInMillis start = internal::GetTimeInMillis();
2640 
2641  impl->os_stack_trace_getter()->UponLeavingGTest();
2642 
2643  // Creates the test object.
2644  Test* const test = internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2645  factory_, &internal::TestFactoryBase::CreateTest,
2646  "the test fixture's constructor");
2647 
2648  // Runs the test only if the test object was created and its
2649  // constructor didn't generate a fatal failure.
2650  if ((test != NULL) && !Test::HasFatalFailure()) {
2651  // This doesn't throw as all user code that can throw are wrapped into
2652  // exception handling code.
2653  test->Run();
2654  }
2655 
2656  // Deletes the test object.
2657  impl->os_stack_trace_getter()->UponLeavingGTest();
2658  internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
2659  test, &Test::DeleteSelf_, "the test fixture's destructor");
2660 
2661  result_.set_elapsed_time(internal::GetTimeInMillis() - start);
2662 
2663  // Notifies the unit test event listener that a test has just finished.
2664  repeater->OnTestEnd(*this);
2665 
2666  // Tells UnitTest to stop associating assertion results to this
2667  // test.
2668  impl->set_current_test_info(NULL);
2669 }

2761

2763

2770  for (int i = 0; i < total_test_count(); i++) {

2774

2776  internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(

2801 // Formats a countable noun. Depending on its quantity, either the

2808  const char * plural_form) {

2879  COLOR_RED,

2887 // Returns the character attribute for the given color.

2902  switch (color) {
2903  case COLOR_RED: return "1";
2904  case COLOR_GREEN: return "2";
2905  case COLOR_YELLOW: return "3";

2912 // Returns true iff Google Test should use colors in the output.
2913 bool ShouldUseColor(bool stdout_is_tty) {
2914  const char* const gtest_color = GTEST_FLAG(color).c_str();
2915 
2916  if (String::CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(gtest_color, "auto")) {
2917 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
2918  // On Windows the TERM variable is usually not set, but the
2919  // console there does support colors.
2920  return stdout_is_tty;
2921 #else
2922  // On non-Windows platforms, we rely on the TERM variable.
2923  const char* const term = posix::GetEnv("TERM");
2924  const bool term_supports_color =
2925  String::CStringEquals(term, "xterm") ||
2926  String::CStringEquals(term, "xterm-color") ||
2927  String::CStringEquals(term, "xterm-256color") ||
2928  String::CStringEquals(term, "screen") ||
2929  String::CStringEquals(term, "screen-256color") ||
2930  String::CStringEquals(term, "tmux") ||
2931  String::CStringEquals(term, "tmux-256color") ||
2932  String::CStringEquals(term, "rxvt-unicode") ||
2933  String::CStringEquals(term, "rxvt-unicode-256color") ||
2934  String::CStringEquals(term, "linux") ||
2935  String::CStringEquals(term, "cygwin");
2936  return stdout_is_tty && term_supports_color;
2937 #endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
2938  }
2939 
2940  return String::CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(gtest_color, "yes") ||
2941  String::CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(gtest_color, "true") ||
2942  String::CaseInsensitiveCStringEquals(gtest_color, "t") ||
2943  String::CStringEquals(gtest_color, "1");
2944  // We take "yes", "true", "t", and "1" as meaning "yes". If the
2945  // value is neither one of these nor "auto", we treat it as "no" to
2946  // be conservative.
2947 }

2949 // Helpers for printing colored strings to stdout. Note that on Windows, we
2950 // cannot simply emit special characters and have the terminal change colors.
2951 // This routine must actually emit the characters rather than return a string
2952 // that would be colored when printed, as can be done on Linux.
2953 GTEST_ATTRIBUTE_PRINTF_(2, 3)
2954 void ColoredPrintf(GTestColor color, const char* fmt, ...) {
2955  va_list args;
2956  va_start(args, fmt);
2957 
2958 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE || GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN || GTEST_OS_ZOS || \
2959  GTEST_OS_IOS || GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE || GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT
2960  const bool use_color = AlwaysFalse();
2961 #else
2962  static const bool in_color_mode =
2963  ShouldUseColor(posix::IsATTY(posix::FileNo(stdout)) != 0);
2964  const bool use_color = in_color_mode && (color != COLOR_DEFAULT);
2965 #endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE || GTEST_OS_SYMBIAN || GTEST_OS_ZOS
2966  // The '!= 0' comparison is necessary to satisfy MSVC 7.1.
2967 
2968  if (!use_color) {
2969  vprintf(fmt, args);
2970  va_end(args);
2971  return;
2972  }
2973 
2974 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE && \
2975  !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT
2976  const HANDLE stdout_handle = GetStdHandle(STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE);
2977 
2978  // Gets the current text color.
2979  CONSOLE_SCREEN_BUFFER_INFO buffer_info;
2980  GetConsoleScreenBufferInfo(stdout_handle, &buffer_info);
2981  const WORD old_color_attrs = buffer_info.wAttributes;
2982 
2983  // We need to flush the stream buffers into the console before each
2984  // SetConsoleTextAttribute call lest it affect the text that is already
2985  // printed but has not yet reached the console.
2986  fflush(stdout);
2987  SetConsoleTextAttribute(stdout_handle,
2988  GetColorAttribute(color) | FOREGROUND_INTENSITY);
2989  vprintf(fmt, args);
2990 
2991  fflush(stdout);
2992  // Restores the text color.
2993  SetConsoleTextAttribute(stdout_handle, old_color_attrs);
2994 #else
2995  printf("\033[0;3%sm", GetAnsiColorCode(color));
2996  vprintf(fmt, args);
2997  printf("\033[m"); // Resets the terminal to default.
2998 #endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
2999  va_end(args);
3000 }

3462 // Returns an XML-escaped copy of the input string str. If is_attribute
3463 // is true, the text is meant to appear as an attribute value, and
3464 // normalizable whitespace is preserved by replacing it with character
3465 // references.
3466 //
3467 // Invalid XML characters in str, if any, are stripped from the output.
3468 // It is expected that most, if not all, of the text processed by this
3469 // module will consist of ordinary English text.
3470 // If this module is ever modified to produce version 1.1 XML output,
3471 // most invalid characters can be retained using character references.
3472 // TODO(wan): It might be nice to have a minimally invasive, human-readable
3473 // escaping scheme for invalid characters, rather than dropping them.
3474 std::string XmlUnitTestResultPrinter::EscapeXml(
3475  const std::string& str, bool is_attribute) {
3476  Message m;
3477 
3478  for (size_t i = 0; i < str.size(); ++i) {
3479  const char ch = str[i];
3480  switch (ch) {
3481  case '<':
3482  m << "&lt;";
3483  break;
3484  case '>':
3485  m << "&gt;";
3486  break;
3487  case '&':
3488  m << "&amp;";
3489  break;
3490  case '\'':
3491  if (is_attribute)
3492  m << "&apos;";
3493  else
3494  m << '\'';
3495  break;
3496  case '"':
3497  if (is_attribute)
3498  m << "&quot;";
3499  else
3500  m << '"';
3501  break;
3502  default:
3503  if (IsValidXmlCharacter(ch)) {
3504  if (is_attribute && IsNormalizableWhitespace(ch))
3505  m << "&#x" << String::FormatByte(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch))
3506  << ";";
3507  else
3508  m << ch;
3509  }
3510  break;
3511  }
3512  }
3513 
3514  return m.GetString();
3515 }

3517 // Returns the given string with all characters invalid in XML removed.
3518 // Currently invalid characters are dropped from the string. An
3519 // alternative is to replace them with certain characters such as . or ?.
3520 std::string XmlUnitTestResultPrinter::RemoveInvalidXmlCharacters(
3521  const std::string& str) {
3522  std::string output;
3523  output.reserve(str.size());
3524  for (std::string::const_iterator it = str.begin(); it != str.end(); ++it)
3525  if (IsValidXmlCharacter(*it))
3526  output.push_back(*it);
3527 
3528  return output;
3529 }

3554 static bool PortableLocaltime(time_t seconds, struct tm* out) {
3555 #if defined(_MSC_VER)
3556  return localtime_s(out, &seconds) == 0;
3557 #elif defined(__MINGW32__) || defined(__MINGW64__)
3558  // MINGW <time.h> provides neither localtime_r nor localtime_s, but uses
3559  // Windows' localtime(), which has a thread-local tm buffer.
3560  struct tm* tm_ptr = localtime(&seconds); // NOLINT
3561  if (tm_ptr == NULL)
3562  return false;
3563  *out = *tm_ptr;
3564  return true;
3565 #else
3566  return localtime_r(&seconds, out) != NULL;
3567 #endif
3568 }

3570 // Converts the given epoch time in milliseconds to a date string in the ISO
3571 // 8601 format, without the timezone information.
3572 std::string FormatEpochTimeInMillisAsIso8601(TimeInMillis ms) {
3573  struct tm time_struct;
3574  if (!PortableLocaltime(static_cast<time_t>(ms / 1000), &time_struct))
3575  return "";
3576  // YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss
3577  return StreamableToString(time_struct.tm_year + 1900) + "-" +
3578  String::FormatIntWidth2(time_struct.tm_mon + 1) + "-" +
3579  String::FormatIntWidth2(time_struct.tm_mday) + "T" +
3580  String::FormatIntWidth2(time_struct.tm_hour) + ":" +
3581  String::FormatIntWidth2(time_struct.tm_min) + ":" +
3582  String::FormatIntWidth2(time_struct.tm_sec);
3583 }

3585 // Streams an XML CDATA section, escaping invalid CDATA sequences as needed.
3586 void XmlUnitTestResultPrinter::OutputXmlCDataSection(::std::ostream* stream,
3587  const char* data) {
3588  const char* segment = data;
3589  *stream << "<![CDATA[";
3590  for (;;) {
3591  const char* const next_segment = strstr(segment, "]]>");
3592  if (next_segment != NULL) {
3593  stream->write(
3594  segment, static_cast<std::streamsize>(next_segment - segment));
3595  *stream << "]]>]]&gt;<![CDATA[";
3596  segment = next_segment + strlen("]]>");
3597  } else {
3598  *stream << segment;
3599  break;
3600  }
3601  }
3602  *stream << "]]>";
3603 }

3755 // Checks if str contains '=', '&', '%' or '\n' characters. If yes,
3756 // replaces them by "%xx" where xx is their hexadecimal value. For
3757 // example, replaces "=" with "%3D". This algorithm is O(strlen(str))
3758 // in both time and space -- important as the input str may contain an
3759 // arbitrarily long test failure message and stack trace.
3760 std::string StreamingListener::UrlEncode(const char* str) {
3761  std::string result;
3762  result.reserve(strlen(str) + 1);
3763  for (char ch = *str; ch != '\0'; ch = *++str) {
3764  switch (ch) {
3765  case '%':
3766  case '=':
3767  case '&':
3768  case '\n':
3769  result.append("%" + String::FormatByte(static_cast<unsigned char>(ch)));
3770  break;
3771  default:
3772  result.push_back(ch);
3773  break;
3774  }
3775  }
3776  return result;
3777 }

3779 void StreamingListener::SocketWriter::MakeConnection() {
3780  GTEST_CHECK_(sockfd_ == -1)
3781  << "MakeConnection() can't be called when there is already a connection.";
3782 
3783  addrinfo hints;
3784  memset(&hints, 0, sizeof(hints));
3785  hints.ai_family = AF_UNSPEC; // To allow both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses.
3786  hints.ai_socktype = SOCK_STREAM;
3787  addrinfo* servinfo = NULL;
3788 
3789  // Use the getaddrinfo() to get a linked list of IP addresses for
3790  // the given host name.
3791  const int error_num = getaddrinfo(
3792  host_name_.c_str(), port_num_.c_str(), &hints, &servinfo);
3793  if (error_num != 0) {
3794  GTEST_LOG_(WARNING) << "stream_result_to: getaddrinfo() failed: "
3795  << gai_strerror(error_num);
3796  }
3797 
3798  // Loop through all the results and connect to the first we can.
3799  for (addrinfo* cur_addr = servinfo; sockfd_ == -1 && cur_addr != NULL;
3800  cur_addr = cur_addr->ai_next) {
3801  sockfd_ = socket(
3802  cur_addr->ai_family, cur_addr->ai_socktype, cur_addr->ai_protocol);
3803  if (sockfd_ != -1) {
3804  // Connect the client socket to the server socket.
3805  if (connect(sockfd_, cur_addr->ai_addr, cur_addr->ai_addrlen) == -1) {
3806  close(sockfd_);
3807  sockfd_ = -1;
3808  }
3809  }
3810  }
3811 
3812  freeaddrinfo(servinfo); // all done with this structure
3813 
3814  if (sockfd_ == -1) {
3815  GTEST_LOG_(WARNING) << "stream_result_to: failed to connect to "
3816  << host_name_ << ":" << port_num_;
3817  }
3818 }

3856 // A helper class that creates the premature-exit file in its
3857 // constructor and deletes the file in its destructor.
3858 class ScopedPrematureExitFile {
3859  public:
3860  explicit ScopedPrematureExitFile(const char* premature_exit_filepath)
3861  : premature_exit_filepath_(premature_exit_filepath) {
3862  // If a path to the premature-exit file is specified...
3863  if (premature_exit_filepath != NULL && *premature_exit_filepath != '\0') {
3864  // create the file with a single "0" character in it. I/O
3865  // errors are ignored as there's nothing better we can do and we
3866  // don't want to fail the test because of this.
3867  FILE* pfile = posix::FOpen(premature_exit_filepath, "w");
3868  fwrite("0", 1, 1, pfile);
3869  fclose(pfile);
3870  }
3871  }
3872 
3873  ~ScopedPrematureExitFile() {
3874  if (premature_exit_filepath_ != NULL && *premature_exit_filepath_ != '\0') {
3875  remove(premature_exit_filepath_);
3876  }
3877  }
3878 
3879  private:
3880  const char* const premature_exit_filepath_;
3881 
3882  GTEST_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN_(ScopedPrematureExitFile);
3883 };

3964 // Gets the singleton UnitTest object. The first time this method is
3965 // called, a UnitTest object is constructed and returned. Consecutive
3966 // calls will return the same object.
3967 //
3968 // We don't protect this under mutex_ as a user is not supposed to
3969 // call this before main() starts, from which point on the return
3970 // value will never change.
3971 UnitTest* UnitTest::GetInstance() {
3972  // When compiled with MSVC 7.1 in optimized mode, destroying the
3973  // UnitTest object upon exiting the program messes up the exit code,
3974  // causing successful tests to appear failed. We have to use a
3975  // different implementation in this case to bypass the compiler bug.
3976  // This implementation makes the compiler happy, at the cost of
3977  // leaking the UnitTest object.
3978

3980  // default implementation. Use this implementation to keep good OO
3981  // design with private destructor.

3983 #if (_MSC_VER == 1310 && !defined(_DEBUG)) || defined(__BORLANDC__)

3985  return instance;
3986 #else

3988  return &instance;
3989 #endif // (_MSC_VER == 1310 && !defined(_DEBUG)) || defined(__BORLANDC__)
3990 }

4103 // Adds a TestPartResult to the current TestResult object. All Google Test
4104 // assertion macros (e.g. ASSERT_TRUE, EXPECT_EQ, etc) eventually call
4105 // this to report their results. The user code should use the
4106 // assertion macros instead of calling this directly.
4107 void UnitTest::AddTestPartResult(
4108  TestPartResult::Type result_type,
4109  const char* file_name,
4110  int line_number,
4111  const std::string& message,
4112  const std::string& os_stack_trace) GTEST_LOCK_EXCLUDED_(mutex_) {
4113  Message msg;
4114  msg << message;
4115 
4116  internal::MutexLock lock(&mutex_);
4117  if (impl_->gtest_trace_stack().size() > 0) {
4118  msg << "\n" << GTEST_NAME_ << " trace:";
4119 
4120  for (int i = static_cast<int>(impl_->gtest_trace_stack().size());
4121  i > 0; --i) {
4122  const internal::TraceInfo& trace = impl_->gtest_trace_stack()[i - 1];
4123  msg << "\n" << internal::FormatFileLocation(trace.file, trace.line)
4124  << " " << trace.message;
4125  }
4126  }
4127 
4128  if (os_stack_trace.c_str() != NULL && !os_stack_trace.empty()) {
4129  msg << internal::kStackTraceMarker << os_stack_trace;
4130  }
4131 
4132  const TestPartResult result =
4133  TestPartResult(result_type, file_name, line_number,
4134  msg.GetString().c_str());
4135  impl_->GetTestPartResultReporterForCurrentThread()->
4136  ReportTestPartResult(result);
4137 
4138  if (result_type != TestPartResult::kSuccess) {
4139  // gtest_break_on_failure takes precedence over
4140  // gtest_throw_on_failure. This allows a user to set the latter
4141  // in the code (perhaps in order to use Google Test assertions
4142  // with another testing framework) and specify the former on the
4143  // command line for debugging.
4144  if (GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure)) {
4145 #if GTEST_OS_WINDOWS && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT
4146  // Using DebugBreak on Windows allows gtest to still break into a debugger
4147  // when a failure happens and both the --gtest_break_on_failure and
4148  // the --gtest_catch_exceptions flags are specified.
4149  DebugBreak();
4150 #else
4151  // Dereference NULL through a volatile pointer to prevent the compiler
4152  // from removing. We use this rather than abort() or __builtin_trap() for
4153  // portability: Symbian doesn't implement abort() well, and some debuggers
4154  // don't correctly trap abort().
4155  *static_cast<volatile int*>(NULL) = 1;
4156 #endif // GTEST_OS_WINDOWS
4157  } else if (GTEST_FLAG(throw_on_failure)) {
4158 #if GTEST_HAS_EXCEPTIONS
4159  throw internal::GoogleTestFailureException(result);
4160 #else
4161  // We cannot call abort() as it generates a pop-up in debug mode
4162  // that cannot be suppressed in VC 7.1 or below.
4163  exit(1);
4164 #endif
4165  }
4166  }
4167 }

4179 // Runs all tests in this UnitTest object and prints the result.
4180 // Returns 0 if successful, or 1 otherwise.
4181 //
4182 // We don't protect this under mutex_, as we only support calling it
4183 // from the main thread.
4184 int UnitTest::Run() {
4185  const bool in_death_test_child_process =
4186  internal::GTEST_FLAG(internal_run_death_test).length() > 0;
4187 
4188  // Google Test implements this protocol for catching that a test
4189  // program exits before returning control to Google Test:
4190  //
4191  // 1. Upon start, Google Test creates a file whose absolute path
4192  // is specified by the environment variable
4193  // TEST_PREMATURE_EXIT_FILE.
4194  // 2. When Google Test has finished its work, it deletes the file.
4195  //
4196  // This allows a test runner to set TEST_PREMATURE_EXIT_FILE before
4197  // running a Google-Test-based test program and check the existence
4198  // of the file at the end of the test execution to see if it has
4199  // exited prematurely.
4200 
4201  // If we are in the child process of a death test, don't
4202  // create/delete the premature exit file, as doing so is unnecessary
4203  // and will confuse the parent process. Otherwise, create/delete
4204  // the file upon entering/leaving this function. If the program
4205  // somehow exits before this function has a chance to return, the
4206  // premature-exit file will be left undeleted, causing a test runner
4207  // that understands the premature-exit-file protocol to report the
4208  // test as having failed.
4209  const internal::ScopedPrematureExitFile premature_exit_file(
4210  in_death_test_child_process ?
4211  NULL : internal::posix::GetEnv("TEST_PREMATURE_EXIT_FILE"));
4212 
4213  // Captures the value of GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions). This value will be
4214  // used for the duration of the program.
4215  impl()->set_catch_exceptions(GTEST_FLAG(catch_exceptions));
4216 
4217 #if GTEST_HAS_SEH
4218  // Either the user wants Google Test to catch exceptions thrown by the
4219  // tests or this is executing in the context of death test child
4220  // process. In either case the user does not want to see pop-up dialogs
4221  // about crashes - they are expected.
4222  if (impl()->catch_exceptions() || in_death_test_child_process) {
4223 # if !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_PHONE && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_RT
4224  // SetErrorMode doesn't exist on CE.
4225  SetErrorMode(SEM_FAILCRITICALERRORS | SEM_NOALIGNMENTFAULTEXCEPT |
4226  SEM_NOGPFAULTERRORBOX | SEM_NOOPENFILEERRORBOX);
4227 # endif // !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
4228 
4229 # if (defined(_MSC_VER) || GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MINGW) && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
4230  // Death test children can be terminated with _abort(). On Windows,
4231  // _abort() can show a dialog with a warning message. This forces the
4232  // abort message to go to stderr instead.
4233  _set_error_mode(_OUT_TO_STDERR);
4234 # endif
4235 
4236 # if _MSC_VER >= 1400 && !GTEST_OS_WINDOWS_MOBILE
4237  // In the debug version, Visual Studio pops up a separate dialog
4238  // offering a choice to debug the aborted program. We need to suppress
4239  // this dialog or it will pop up for every EXPECT/ASSERT_DEATH statement
4240  // executed. Google Test will notify the user of any unexpected
4241  // failure via stderr.
4242  //
4243  // VC++ doesn't define _set_abort_behavior() prior to the version 8.0.
4244  // Users of prior VC versions shall suffer the agony and pain of
4245  // clicking through the countless debug dialogs.
4246  // TODO(vladl@google.com): find a way to suppress the abort dialog() in the
4247  // debug mode when compiled with VC 7.1 or lower.
4248  if (!GTEST_FLAG(break_on_failure))
4249  _set_abort_behavior(
4250  0x0, // Clear the following flags:
4251  _WRITE_ABORT_MSG | _CALL_REPORTFAULT); // pop-up window, core dump.
4252 # endif
4253  }
4254 #endif // GTEST_HAS_SEH
4255 
4256  return internal::HandleExceptionsInMethodIfSupported(
4257  impl(),
4258  &internal::UnitTestImpl::RunAllTests,
4259  "auxiliary test code (environments or event listeners)") ? 0 : 1;
4260 }

4466 // A predicate that checks the name of a TestCase against a known
4467 // value.
4468 //
4469 // This is used for implementation of the UnitTest class only. We put
4470 // it in the anonymous namespace to prevent polluting the outer
4471 // namespace.
4472 //
4473 // TestCaseNameIs is copyable.
4474 class TestCaseNameIs {
4475  public:
4476  // Constructor.
4477  explicit TestCaseNameIs(const std::string& name)
4478  : name_(name) {}
4479 
4480  // Returns true iff the name of test_case matches name_.
4481  bool operator()(const TestCase* test_case) const {
4482  return test_case != NULL && strcmp(test_case->name(), name_.c_str()) == 0;
4483  }
4484 
4485  private:
4486  std::string name_;
4487 };
4488 
4489 // Finds and returns a TestCase with the given name. If one doesn't
4490 // exist, creates one and returns it. It's the CALLER'S
4491 // RESPONSIBILITY to ensure that this function is only called WHEN THE
4492 // TESTS ARE NOT SHUFFLED.
4493 //
4494 // Arguments:
4495 //
4496 // test_case_name: name of the test case
4497 // type_param: the name of the test case's type parameter, or NULL if
4498 // this is not a typed or a type-parameterized test case.
4499 // set_up_tc: pointer to the function that sets up the test case
4500 // tear_down_tc: pointer to the function that tears down the test case
4501 TestCase* UnitTestImpl::GetTestCase(const char* test_case_name,
4502  const char* type_param,
4503  Test::SetUpTestCaseFunc set_up_tc,
4504  Test::TearDownTestCaseFunc tear_down_tc) {
4505  // Can we find a TestCase with the given name?
4506  const std::vector<TestCase*>::const_iterator test_case =
4507  std::find_if(test_cases_.begin(), test_cases_.end(),
4508  TestCaseNameIs(test_case_name));
4509 
4510  if (test_case != test_cases_.end())
4511  return *test_case;
4512 
4513  // No. Let's create one.
4514  TestCase* const new_test_case =
4515  new TestCase(test_case_name, type_param, set_up_tc, tear_down_tc);
4516 
4517  // Is this a death test case?
4518  if (internal::UnitTestOptions::MatchesFilter(test_case_name,
4519  kDeathTestCaseFilter)) {
4520  // Yes. Inserts the test case after the last death test case
4521  // defined so far. This only works when the test cases haven't
4522  // been shuffled. Otherwise we may end up running a death test
4523  // after a non-death test.
4524  ++last_death_test_case_;
4525  test_cases_.insert(test_cases_.begin() + last_death_test_case_,
4526  new_test_case);
4527  } else {
4528  // No. Appends to the end of the list.
4529  test_cases_.push_back(new_test_case);
4530  }
4531 
4532  test_case_indices_.push_back(static_cast<int>(test_case_indices_.size()));
4533  return new_test_case;
4534 }

4536 // Helpers for setting up / tearing down the given environment. They
4537 // are for use in the ForEach() function.
4538 static void SetUpEnvironment(Environment* env) { env->SetUp(); }
4539 static void TearDownEnvironment(Environment* env) { env->TearDown(); }
4540 
4541 // Runs all tests in this UnitTest object, prints the result, and
4542 // returns true if all tests are successful. If any exception is
4543 // thrown during a test, the test is considered to be failed, but the
4544 // rest of the tests will still be run.
4545 //
4546 // When parameterized tests are enabled, it expands and registers
4547 // parameterized tests first in RegisterParameterizedTests().
4548 // All other functions called from RunAllTests() may safely assume that
4549 // parameterized tests are ready to be counted and run.
4550 bool UnitTestImpl::RunAllTests() {
4551  // Makes sure InitGoogleTest() was called.
4552  if (!GTestIsInitialized()) {
4553  printf("%s",
4554  "\nThis test program did NOT call ::testing::InitGoogleTest "
4555  "before calling RUN_ALL_TESTS(). Please fix it.\n");
4556  return false;
4557  }
4558 
4559  // Do not run any test if the --help flag was specified.
4560  if (g_help_flag)
4561  return true;
4562 
4563  // Repeats the call to the post-flag parsing initialization in case the
4564  // user didn't call InitGoogleTest.
4565  PostFlagParsingInit();
4566 
4567  // Even if sharding is not on, test runners may want to use the
4568  // GTEST_SHARD_STATUS_FILE to query whether the test supports the sharding
4569  // protocol.
4570  internal::WriteToShardStatusFileIfNeeded();
4571 
4572  // True iff we are in a subprocess for running a thread-safe-style
4573  // death test.
4574  bool in_subprocess_for_death_test = false;
4575 
4576 #if GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
4577  in_subprocess_for_death_test = (internal_run_death_test_flag_.get() != NULL);
4578 # if defined(GTEST_EXTRA_DEATH_TEST_CHILD_SETUP_)
4579  if (in_subprocess_for_death_test) {
4580  GTEST_EXTRA_DEATH_TEST_CHILD_SETUP_();
4581  }
4582 # endif // defined(GTEST_EXTRA_DEATH_TEST_CHILD_SETUP_)
4583 #endif // GTEST_HAS_DEATH_TEST
4584 
4585  const bool should_shard = ShouldShard(kTestTotalShards, kTestShardIndex,
4586  in_subprocess_for_death_test);
4587 
4588  // Compares the full test names with the filter to decide which
4589  // tests to run.
4590  const bool has_tests_to_run = FilterTests(should_shard
4591  ? HONOR_SHARDING_PROTOCOL
4592  : IGNORE_SHARDING_PROTOCOL) > 0;
4593 
4594  // Lists the tests and exits if the --gtest_list_tests flag was specified.
4595  if (GTEST_FLAG(list_tests)) {
4596  // This must be called *after* FilterTests() has been called.
4597  ListTestsMatchingFilter();
4598  return true;
4599  }
4600 
4601  random_seed_ = GTEST_FLAG(shuffle) ?
4602  GetRandomSeedFromFlag(GTEST_FLAG(random_seed)) : 0;
4603 
4604  // True iff at least one test has failed.
4605  bool failed = false;
4606 
4607  TestEventListener* repeater = listeners()->repeater();
4608 
4609  start_timestamp_ = GetTimeInMillis();
4610  repeater->OnTestProgramStart(*parent_);
4611 
4612  // How many times to repeat the tests? We don't want to repeat them
4613  // when we are inside the subprocess of a death test.
4614  const int repeat = in_subprocess_for_death_test ? 1 : GTEST_FLAG(repeat);
4615  // Repeats forever if the repeat count is negative.
4616  const bool forever = repeat < 0;
4617  for (int i = 0; forever || i != repeat; i++) {
4618  // We want to preserve failures generated by ad-hoc test
4619  // assertions executed before RUN_ALL_TESTS().
4620  ClearNonAdHocTestResult();
4621 
4622  const TimeInMillis start = GetTimeInMillis();
4623 
4624  // Shuffles test cases and tests if requested.
4625  if (has_tests_to_run && GTEST_FLAG(shuffle)) {
4626  random()->Reseed(random_seed_);
4627  // This should be done before calling OnTestIterationStart(),
4628  // such that a test event listener can see the actual test order
4629  // in the event.
4630  ShuffleTests();
4631  }
4632 
4633  // Tells the unit test event listeners that the tests are about to start.
4634  repeater->OnTestIterationStart(*parent_, i);
4635 
4636  // Runs each test case if there is at least one test to run.
4637  if (has_tests_to_run) {
4638  // Sets up all environments beforehand.
4639  repeater->OnEnvironmentsSetUpStart(*parent_);
4640  ForEach(environments_, SetUpEnvironment);
4641  repeater->OnEnvironmentsSetUpEnd(*parent_);
4642 
4643  // Runs the tests only if there was no fatal failure during global
4644  // set-up.
4645  if (!Test::HasFatalFailure()) {
4646  for (int test_index = 0; test_index < total_test_case_count();
4647  test_index++) {
4648  GetMutableTestCase(test_index)->Run();
4649  }
4650  }
4651 
4652  // Tears down all environments in reverse order afterwards.
4653  repeater->OnEnvironmentsTearDownStart(*parent_);
4654  std::for_each(environments_.rbegin(), environments_.rend(),
4655  TearDownEnvironment);
4656  repeater->OnEnvironmentsTearDownEnd(*parent_);
4657  }
4658 
4659  elapsed_time_ = GetTimeInMillis() - start;
4660 
4661  // Tells the unit test event listener that the tests have just finished.
4662  repeater->OnTestIterationEnd(*parent_, i);
4663 
4664  // Gets the result and clears it.
4665  if (!Passed()) {
4666  failed = true;
4667  }
4668 
4669  // Restores the original test order after the iteration. This
4670  // allows the user to quickly repro a failure that happens in the
4671  // N-th iteration without repeating the first (N - 1) iterations.
4672  // This is not enclosed in "if (GTEST_FLAG(shuffle)) { ... }", in
4673  // case the user somehow changes the value of the flag somewhere
4674  // (it's always safe to unshuffle the tests).
4675  UnshuffleTests();
4676 
4677  if (GTEST_FLAG(shuffle)) {
4678  // Picks a new random seed for each iteration.
4679  random_seed_ = GetNextRandomSeed(random_seed_);
4680  }
4681  }
4682 
4683  repeater->OnTestProgramEnd(*parent_);
4684 
4685  return !failed;
4686 }

4688 // Reads the GTEST_SHARD_STATUS_FILE environment variable, and creates the file
4689 // if the variable is present. If a file already exists at this location, this
4690 // function will write over it. If the variable is present, but the file cannot
4691 // be created, prints an error and exits.
4692 void WriteToShardStatusFileIfNeeded() {
4693  const char* const test_shard_file = posix::GetEnv(kTestShardStatusFile);
4694  if (test_shard_file != NULL) {
4695  FILE* const file = posix::FOpen(test_shard_file, "w");
4696  if (file == NULL) {
4697  ColoredPrintf(COLOR_RED,
4698  "Could not write to the test shard status file \"%s\" "
4699  "specified by the %s environment variable.\n",
4700  test_shard_file, kTestShardStatusFile);
4701  fflush(stdout);
4702  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
4703  }
4704  fclose(file);
4705  }
4706 }

4708 // Checks whether sharding is enabled by examining the relevant
4709 // environment variable values. If the variables are present,
4710 // but inconsistent (i.e., shard_index >= total_shards), prints
4711 // an error and exits. If in_subprocess_for_death_test, sharding is
4712 // disabled because it must only be applied to the original test
4713 // process. Otherwise, we could filter out death tests we intended to execute.
4714 bool ShouldShard(const char* total_shards_env,
4715  const char* shard_index_env,
4716  bool in_subprocess_for_death_test) {
4717  if (in_subprocess_for_death_test) {
4718  return false;
4719  }
4720 
4721  const Int32 total_shards = Int32FromEnvOrDie(total_shards_env, -1);
4722  const Int32 shard_index = Int32FromEnvOrDie(shard_index_env, -1);
4723 
4724  if (total_shards == -1 && shard_index == -1) {
4725  return false;
4726  } else if (total_shards == -1 && shard_index != -1) {
4727  const Message msg = Message()
4728  << "Invalid environment variables: you have "
4729  << kTestShardIndex << " = " << shard_index
4730  << ", but have left " << kTestTotalShards << " unset.\n";
4731  ColoredPrintf(COLOR_RED, "%s", msg.GetString().c_str());
4732  fflush(stdout);
4733  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
4734  } else if (total_shards != -1 && shard_index == -1) {
4735  const Message msg = Message()
4736  << "Invalid environment variables: you have "
4737  << kTestTotalShards << " = " << total_shards
4738  << ", but have left " << kTestShardIndex << " unset.\n";
4739  ColoredPrintf(COLOR_RED, "%s", msg.GetString().c_str());
4740  fflush(stdout);
4741  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
4742  } else if (shard_index < 0 || shard_index >= total_shards) {
4743  const Message msg = Message()
4744  << "Invalid environment variables: we require 0 <= "
4745  << kTestShardIndex << " < " << kTestTotalShards
4746  << ", but you have " << kTestShardIndex << "=" << shard_index
4747  << ", " << kTestTotalShards << "=" << total_shards << ".\n";
4748  ColoredPrintf(COLOR_RED, "%s", msg.GetString().c_str());
4749  fflush(stdout);
4750  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
4751  }
4752 
4753  return total_shards > 1;
4754 }

4756 // Parses the environment variable var as an Int32. If it is unset,
4757 // returns default_val. If it is not an Int32, prints an error
4758 // and aborts.
4759 Int32 Int32FromEnvOrDie(const char* var, Int32 default_val) {
4760  const char* str_val = posix::GetEnv(var);
4761  if (str_val == NULL) {
4762  return default_val;
4763  }
4764 
4765  Int32 result;
4766  if (!ParseInt32(Message() << "The value of environment variable " << var,
4767  str_val, &result)) {
4768  exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
4769  }
4770  return result;
4771 }

4773 // Given the total number of shards, the shard index, and the test id,
4774 // returns true iff the test should be run on this shard. The test id is
4775 // some arbitrary but unique non-negative integer assigned to each test
4776 // method. Assumes that 0 <= shard_index < total_shards.
4777 bool ShouldRunTestOnShard(int total_shards, int shard_index, int test_id) {
4778  return (test_id % total_shards) == shard_index;
4779 }
